<h4>The Accumulation Problem</h4>
<p>Professional orchestral recordings in the 1960s–70s often involved 3–4 tape generations: session → edit master → mixing → lacquer cut. Each generation added noise and coloration. Engineers balanced this against digital's lack of "air." Three stages of modest saturation sound better than one stage of heavy saturation — the harmonics stay musical.</p>
